Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Kevin Richard Tarbox in court with attorney Jeffery Joy.  Defendant Kevin Richard Tarbox in custody.  Lucy Kronforst appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Sentencing proceeds. Statements made by the State, defense and defendant. 

AS TO COUNT 1 (AMENDED):    The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 5 1/2 YEARS, consecutive to any other sentence defendant is currently serving. 
INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 2 1/2 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 3 YEARS.
Credit for ZERO days time served.

Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.
Court finds defendant is eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION (AS TO COUNT 1):
* Comply with the standard rules of extended supervision.
* Cooperate and participate with an AODA assessment and follow any recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety and submit to random urine screens.
* PAY the balance of all applicable court costs, fees, and surcharges.  The Court ordered that all court costs, fees, and surcharges paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is to convert to a civil judgment.
* Provide a DNA sample (unless previously done) and PAY DNA surcharge.  The Court ordered that the DNA surcharge is paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is to convert to a civil judgment.
* PAY fine in the amount of $1,200.00.  The Court ordered that the fine is paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is to convert to a civil judgment.

OTHER COURT ORDERS:
* Defendant's driver operating privileges are REVOKED for a period of 3 years from today's date.
* Any vehicle titled in the defendant's name or driven by the defendant is to have an ignition interlock device installed for a period of 3 years.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.  
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
Appeal rights given.

Defendant Kevin Richard Tarbox in court with attorney Jeffery Joy.  Defendant Kevin Richard Tarbox in custody.  Lucy Kronforst appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

This matter was originally scheduled for a motion hearing for collateral attack today, however, the parties have now reached an agreement.

Based upon the inability of the State to produce a transcript on the underlying case, Court ACCEPTS the stipulation of the parties to warrant this case to be treated as an OWI 6th Offense.

Court ordered Count #1 AMENDED to an OWI as a 6th Offense, contrary to Wisc. Stats. Sec. 346.63(1)(a), 939.50(3)(h), 346.65(2)(g), and 343.301(1g).

**NO AMENDED INFORMATION FILED.

AS TO COUNT 1 (AMENDED):  Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms. Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.
